That said only way this gets stopped and you reclaim the kinks into positivity is not the standard American practice of ignoring the negativity. We have to actively acknowledge it, make reasonable amends to discourage the behavior, and keep on having fun.

Not every producer of it even was like cursing blacks. But if that and a media saying what it does are your only reference people will start making bad connections. Sometimes the kink community itself is the only group that will even see the issue enough to id it.

Add to that a media that is not helping them gain any positive notions about brown people, then the lack of personal exposure to races in the rural areas. They, like with many other things, are NOT gonna suddenly be able to stop themselves absorbing brainworms..

In example, lets talk cuckolding and racism. In the past, a large population of the kink consumed a LOT of content that had the racial twist. Now that is not all of the content, but for a nontrivial amount of participants it has become a part of their regular experience

throughly to polarize the issue. But I propose there is a fair freedom from responsibility for bad actors, one must also accept and push past the fact that publicly identifying with a kink and community carries weight. Kinks and their communities have histories, thats just facts.

On the topic of kink shaming.
